by Tran Nguyen¶

Table of Contents¶

  • Introduction

  • Conclusions

1. Introduction¶

  • Dataset: The file OnlineRetail.csv containing 541,909 rows and 8 features.

  • The data consists of the information of all purchases of an online retail company in the UK during an 12 month period. The dataset can be found in the Kaggle site (https://www.kaggle.com/vijayuv/onlineretail?select=OnlineRetail.csv).

  • The question I want to ask is what features are best for predicting the revenue of the company.

    • Is there any interesting feature in the dataset?
    • What is the progress of this online retail company? Does its business grow?
    • Is there any trend for product sales during different hours, days of weeks, days of the month?

With that, let's dive into the dataset.

2. Data Wrangling¶

1. Problem need to be fixed¶

  • InvoiceDate is in str => need to change to datetime type
  • CustomerID is in float => need to change to str
  • Change the dtype object to str
  • For the items with no Description, the UnitPrice is 0.0 => No meaning for data analysis => Remove all of these rows.
  • Remove the item that has UnitPrice = 0
  • Create a new column of Year and Month as InvoiceYearMonth for calculating monthly revenue.
  • Create a new column for hour of day, day of week and day of month.

2. Create some separate dataframes for analysis¶

2.1. Create a separate dataframe df_revenue for monthly metrics (revenue, growth rate, number of orders, number of active customers)¶

DEFINE THE METRICS:

  • Revenue: Revenue = UnitPrice * Quantity.
  • Monthly Revenue: The revenue for each month = the sum of all revenues in that month.
  • Monthly Revenue Growth Rate: The percentage change between the current and a prior element.

2.2. Create separate dataframe df_sales for sale with no charges/fees¶

It is better to remove all the non-product transaction out (debt, AMAZONFEE) before analyzing product sales for different hours of different days of the week

3. Exploratory Data Analysis¶

The structure of the dataset¶

  • There are 539,394 transaction items in the dataset with 8 features ('InvoiceNo', 'StockCode', 'Description', 'Quantity', 'InvoiceDate','UnitPrice', 'CustomerID', 'Country').

The most important features in this dataset¶

  • The 2 numeric variables 'UnitPrice' and 'Quantity', which provide us the revenue of the company.
  • The 'InvoiceDate' provides us precious information about business trend and development: the revenue for weeks, months and years.
  • The 'Country' field helps us to segment the data into different region groups.
  • 'CustomerID' helps us to segment the data into different customer groups.

I'm most interested in figuring out what features are best for predicting the revenue of the company.

Features in the dataset that may help support the investigation into the features of interest¶

I expect that the number of active customers will have the strongest effect on the number of sale product, and hence, effect the company revenue: the larger the number of active customers, the higher the sale quantity, the higher the revenue. I also think that there will be different purchasing behavior depends on the time variable: hours of day, day of the week.

Let's do exploratory data analysis to get more insight into the data.

3.6. The sum revenue for different hours of different days of the week¶

  • Using the df_sales dataframe in which all the non-product transaction out (debt, AMAZONFEE) was removed.
In [57]:
### Prepare data: Revenue by hour/day of week/InvoiceYearMonth

hour_mean_revenues = df_sales.groupby(['DayOfWeek', 'Hour'])['Revenue'].sum()\
        .reset_index().rename(columns={'Revenue': 'Sum_Revenue'})

sns.set(style="whitegrid")

hours = list(range(6, 21))
g = sns.FacetGrid(data = hour_mean_revenues, hue = 'DayOfWeek',
                  hue_order = ['Monday', 'Tuesday', 'Wednesday', 'Thursday', 'Friday', 'Saturday', 'Sunday'],
                  palette = 'Paired', height = 6, aspect = 2)
g.map(plt.plot, 'Hour', 'Sum_Revenue')\
        .set(xlim=(5, 21), xticks= hours);
plt.ylabel('Sum Revenue (EUR)', fontsize = 14, fontweight = 'bold')
g.add_legend(loc = 'upper right', title = '', fontsize='14');
plt.xlabel('Hours', fontsize = 14, fontweight = 'bold')
# Hard code tick_locs for easy visualization
tick_locs = [0, 50000, 100000, 150000, 200000, 250000, 300000, 350000]
tick_labels = ['0', '50K', '100K', '150K', '200K', '250K', '300K', '3500K']
plt.yticks(tick_locs, tick_labels);

According to the graph, the active sale time was in the middle of the day where the sum revenue values are lightly higher than in the rest of the day. The sum revenue is lower in the days around weekend, which are Friday, Sunday and Monday (there is no Saturday data). Tuesday, Wednesday and Thursday where the customers purchased the most products. Let see if this trend is consistent in different months.

Conclusions¶

  • This dataset consists of the information of all purchases of an online retail company in the UK during an 12 month period. The customers were from 38 different countries across the world. Among these, 90% customers were from the United Kingdom.
  • The price of products and the order quantity are extremely divergent, with many large positive outliers.
  • Overall, the company has a healthy growth trend, especially in the latest 6 months of available data. The growth rate look quite good (above the base line 0), except in the month of April 2011 where the growth rate went down dramatically, which dues to the reduce of number of customer and orders in that month.
  • As expected, the number of active customers in each month is highly correlated with the number of orders.
  • According to the graph, the best sale hours were in the middle of the day.
  • The sum revenue is lower in the days around weekend, which are Friday, Sunday and Monday (there is no Saturday data). Tuesday, Wednesday and Thursday where the customers purchased the most products.

LIMITATIONS OF THIS ANALYSIS:¶

  • No inference statistic analysis and machine learning techniques was performed. These analyses could be used to segment customer, predict the customer lifetime value, predict sales, etc.
